<strong>IN&#45;TEXT CITATION</strong>
<br><br>
When you use another person&#8217;s work in your writing, include the name of the person who created the image and any relevant page number(s), in parentheses, immediately following the cited material. If you include the title, place the image title in double quotation marks. Abbreviate the title if it is longer than a noun phrase. For example, <em>Faulkner&#8217;s Southern Novels</em> consists entirely of a noun phrase (a noun <em>Novels</em> preceded by two modifiers) and wouldn&#8217;t be shortened. By contrast <em>Faulkner&#8217;s Novels of the South</em> would be shortened to its noun phrase <em>Faulkner&#8217;s Novels</em>. The abbreviated title should begin with the word by which it is alphabetised in the Works Cited. If the title does not begin with a noun phrase, cite the first word if it is enough to direct the reader to the correct entry. For further information on abbreviating titles, see 3.2.1 in the <a href="http://west-sydney-primo.hosted.exlibrisgroup.com/UWS-ALMA:default_scope:UWS-ALMA21186157620001571" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">MLA Handbook (8th edition)</a>.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	&hellip;conveys a sense of heightened emotion (Tschichold, "Die Frau" 32). 
</blockquote>
<br><br>
Or include the name of the person who created the image in your sentence, with the relevant page number(s) in parentheses. If the image title is included in the sentence, provide the full title.
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	"Die Frau Ohne Namen" by Tschichold shows&hellip; (32)."
</blockquote>
